        "body": "The narrator speaks five verses before Elihu opens his mouth, which is itself significant. In the dialogue sections of Job, the narrator rarely intervenes at such length. Here he does so to establish the theological score before the new voice begins: the three friends have stopped speaking (32:1), and Elihu is angry at both parties (32:2–3). The narrator's double use of 'righteous' vocabulary is the chapter's first interpretive key. Job is 'righteous in his own eyes' (*tsaddiq be-einav*, 32:1) — which, as the reader of chapters 1–2 knows, is not entirely false. God Himself called Job 'blameless and upright' (1:1, 8). The problem the narrator names in 32:2 is not that Job is wrong about his own character but that he has crossed from defending his integrity to 'justifying himself before God' (*tsadaq nephesho mi-el*) — placing himself as the superior party in a legal dispute with the Almighty. This is the distinction Robert Gordis, Peter Craigie, and John Hartley all press: Job's integrity is real, but his posture of demanding God as defendant has become theologically untenable.\n\nThe friends' failure is equally precise. They had no answer and 'yet condemned Job' (32:3). The Hebrew is pointed: they condemned (*rasha*, declared wicked) a man they could not refute. Their theological conclusion outran their actual argument. Eliphaz, Bildad, and Zophar repeated the same retributive framework — suffering equals hidden sin — across three cycles without ever engaging Job's actual counter-arguments. As Douglas Moo notes in a broader context, theological tradition that cannot engage the specific question in front of it has already lost the argument before it speaks.\n\nElihad had been present through all of this (32:4). His waiting is not absence; it is patient observation that has produced a verdict. The four-fold repetition of his burning anger (32:2, 3, 5) is the narrator's signal that the engine of chapters 32–37 is moral seriousness, not wounded pride. Whether that seriousness survives contact with Elihu's own eloquence is the question the reader must keep open.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tsaddiq be-einav* (righteous in his own eyes, 32:1) — a phrase the OT uses of self-deception (Proverbs 30:12) but also of genuine self-knowledge (Proverbs 21:2). The narrator's use here is deliberately ambiguous. *Tsadaq nephesho mi-el* (justifying himself before/rather than God, 32:2) — *mi-el* could mean 'more than God' or 'before God'; both senses are in play. *Charah aph* (burning of the nose/anger) — four occurrences in three verses."
