        "number": 2,
        "title": "Concession and reversal — the source of wisdom",
        "range": "32:6-10",
        "excerpt": "But it is a spirit in man, and the breath of the Almighty gives them understanding.",
        "body": "Elihu opens with a formal concession (32:6–7) and then reverses it with a theological argument (32:8–9) and a practical conclusion (32:10). The rhetorical structure is classical — grant the opponent's premise, then show it fails on theological grounds. He concedes the convention: age should speak, multiplied years should teach wisdom (32:7). This is not a straw man; it is the genuine social and intellectual protocol of the ancient Near East's wisdom tradition. Eliphaz appeals to it directly in 15:9–10, and the entire Joban dialogue has been conducted on the assumption that the oldest speakers bear the greatest authority.\n\nThe reversal in 32:8 is governed by the adversative *akhen* — 'but, surely, indeed.' What actually produces understanding is 'a spirit in man' and 'the breath of the Almighty.' The parallelism is careful: *ruach* (spirit, the animating divine wind) and *neshamah* (breath, the specific term for the breath of life in Genesis 2:7) are paired to anchor wisdom-giving in the original creative act. God breathed *neshamah* into Adam; that same breath-endowment is the channel through which genuine understanding comes. The implication is radical: access to divine wisdom is a creation-endowment, not an accumulation. It cannot be purchased by years.\n\nVerse 32:9 applies the principle empirically: the 'abundant in years' (*rabbim*) are not wise, and elders do not automatically understand *mishpat* (justice, right ordering). The friends are the proof-text. Their years produced dogma that could not engage Job's specific situation — exactly the failure Elihu has just witnessed through the entire dialogue. John Calvin comments on this passage that 'the spirit of discernment is not the property of old men by any hereditary right; God distributes it as He wills' — a reminder that the anti-elitist thrust of 32:8–9 is not Elihu's personal claim but a theological principle about divine sovereignty in wisdom-distribution.\n\nThe conclusion follows in 32:10: 'Therefore, listen to me; I also will tell what I know.' The inferential *ken* ('therefore') makes the epistemological argument do practical work. Elihu is not claiming to be wiser than the three friends in any absolute sense; he is claiming that the source of wisdom he appeals to — the spirit given by the Almighty — is available to him just as much as to any elder.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Akhen* (32:8) — a strong adversative/asseverative particle, 'but surely.' *Ruach* and *neshamah* in parallel — the same pairing appears in Job 33:4, linking Elihu's later claim ('the Spirit of God has made me') to this foundational statement. *Mishpat* (justice, 32:9) — the legal-covenantal term for right ordering; its mention anticipates Elihu's later concern with God's just governance (34:17; 36:3)."
